My Dear Sherwood:
We have had your nice letters - and we are so glad to hear that you are writing and feeling no fit again. Here in h-y. Rooselveldt has opened a pig hole in the general cloud that was hanging over everything. There is a kind of miracle change from despair to hope in the air and Republican and Democrat alike are all pepped up about him. However the other night at a bridge table a quiet jew

said calmly and with a quiet understanding air of the prophet when there was much talk of the upward trend - yes - for a moment- but ultimately- and not to distant - this old true will fall - I suppose that - you to - thinker and see-er that you are look beyond the moment toward a better place - most of us are content with the moment- if its cruive (?) our way of (?) that's what's wrong with the urred. 

                Burt is feeling pretty seedy this winter-He has had a

long siege with his heart keeping time quiet- and the general depression has made him pretty low- I hope that the warm days of Spring will pep him up again- He wants me to say that he will write you soon- He just don't feel up to doing much of anything at present - 
Hurrah for the grand child- I hope she will live to me a better world - I can't complain myself- It's heated me well but-

He will be looking forward to reading your book. I'm sure that the truth about advertising has some good stories. We are so glad that you are feeling enthusiastic again - and that you are a jest for writing once more. Remember us to Eleanor and we send our love to both of you. 
Mary Furmett
March 22nd 1933

May 15th, 1933
Dear Sherwood:
It was marvelous of you to set down and pour out to me that long this page letter. And the letter itself is so splendid that I do not feel able, or even worthy, to answer it. That is the reason, really, why for severed days I have been allowing myself to post pone my thanks and appreciation. Both Mary and I have read it over and over and the night it came we stayed up for hours talking about it and about you and your beautiful sympathy with and understanding of life. This letter is one of the

2    finest things you ever wrote. But, dear old Sherwood- that damned inglorious momentary squawk I made to you about my own mental state just as we were saying goodbye- I do hope you will believe that I wasn't thinking of or hoping for any such thing on this letter where I spoke for you. What I had in mind, was not helping or expecting anything; it was an entirely different set of thoughts. 

             It is strange how differently people look at those things. You say that is such a pass you persistently cling to others, etc. and that we should not be too proud to assume this beggar's attitude.

I never felt it was due to pride; but, honestly Sherwood, I just can't let myself bother other people about my damned mental woes and troubles. I am sure that is not what you meant. You meant that you turn to others for well I must be mixed up. Anyway, I had been for months so damned "flat", so near jumping off a dock, that I was longing to have some understanding friend to talk to about it all. Except for a doctor and pscychologist whom I would have loved to tell y about, I had not let myself talk about it to any man up here.
